# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dugald-baird
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The council has been under no overall control since 2002.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Since 2022 it has been led by a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrat coalition.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] It meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices at the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a royal burgh by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Elections for the council were only introduced in 1833.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to that the council was not an elected body; when vacancies arose the existing council appointed successors.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was historically part of Aberdeenshire, but the functions affecting the burgh which operated at county level were relatively few, largely being limited to judicial functions and lieutenancy.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] When elected county councils were created in 1890 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1889, Aberdeen Corporation was deemed capable of running county-level local government functions, and so the burgh was excluded from the area administered by Aberdeenshire County Council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] In 1891 Aberdeen's boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the River Dee.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The historic county boundary between Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire in this area followed the River Dee.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Following the absorption of Torry on the south bank of the river in 1891, the city straddled the two counties.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899, removing the city from the two counties for lieutenancy and other purposes as well as local government functions.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The city boundaries were subsequently enlarged several times, gaining further territory from both Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire, notably in 1935, 1952 and 1970.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Local government across Scotland was reorganised in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973, which replaced the counties, burghs and landward districts with a two-tier system of regions and districts.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] One of the districts was called 'City of Aberdeen', which formed part of Grampian Region.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] City of Aberdeen District Council was therefore a lower-tier district authority, with upper-tier regional functions being provided by Grampian Regional Council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The City of Aberdeen district covered a larger area than the pre-1975 city, taking in the parishes of Dyce, Newhills, Old Machar, and Peterculter from Aberdeenshire and Nigg from Kincardineshire.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] All except Dyce had previously ceded territory to the city in pre-1975 boundary changes.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Nigg added in 1975 just covered the residual rural parts of the old parish around Cove Bay; Nigg village itself had been absorbed into the city in 1935.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Old Machar was named after St Machar's Cathedral in Old Aberdeen, which had been absorbed into the city in 1891; the parish of Old Machar that was absorbed in 1975 was just the residual part of the cathedral's old parish which lay north of the River Don, including Bridge of Don.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Local government was reorganised again in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] (Scotland) Act 1994, which abolished the regions and districts created in 1975 and established 32 single-tier council areas across Scotland.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The existing City of Aberdeen District became one of the new council areas.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The 1994 Act named the new council area 'City of Aberdeen', but this was changed to 'Aberdeen City' by a council resolution on 9 May 1995, before the new council area came into force, allowing the new council to take the name 'Aberdeen City Council'.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Following the 2022 election a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrats coalition took control of the council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The first election to the City of Aberdeen District Council was held in 1974, initially operating as a shadow authority alongside the outgoing authorities until the new system came into force on 16 May 1975.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] A shadow authority was again elected in 1995 ahead of the change to council areas which came into force on 1 April 1996.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The role of Lord Provost of Aberdeen is largely ceremonial.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] They chair full council meetings and act as the council's civic figurehead.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Political leadership is provided by the leader of the council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen City Council currently comprises 45 councillors, who represent the city's wards, and is headed by the Lord Provost.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2012 council election there were 43 members of Aberdeen City Council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2003 and 2007, the council was under the control of a Liberal Democrat and Conservative coalition, holding 23 of the 43 seats on the council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2003 election, the council had been considered a Labour stronghold.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Two Liberal Democrat councillors became independents during this period due to personal controversies, while the four strong Conservative group split in August 2010, with two councillors forming the Scottish Conservative Group and two others the Aberdeen Conservative Group.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] After the May 2012 election, the control of the council shifted back to the Labour Party, supported in a coalition by three Conservative and three Independent councillors, giving the administration 23 seats.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The Labour/Conservative/Independent coalition continued after the 2017 election, but with a change in the balance of power within the coalition.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Labour were reduced to nine councillors (subsequently suspended from membership by the Scottish Labour Party for forming a coalition with the Conservatives), whilst the Conservatives had eleven councillors elected.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] These Conservative and suspended "Aberdeen Labour" councillors were joined in coalition by three Independent councillors, one of who had left the Liberal Democrats just days after the council election.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] In December 2019 a councillor elected as a Conservative became an Independent following his conviction for sexual assault.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] This led to the ruling coalition becoming a minority administration comprising only 22 of the 45 councillors.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2017 and 2021 the council had Co-Leaders Douglas Lumsden (Conservative) and Jenny Laing (“Aberdeen Labour”) as a result of the coalition agreement.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Following Douglas Lumsden's election to the Scottish Parliament in May 2021 Jenny Laing became sole Leader of the council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] After the 2022 election the SNP and Liberal Democrats agreed to form a partnership to lead the Council for the next five years.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] At the Council's statutory meeting on 18 May 2022, SNP councillor David Cameron was elected Lord Provost and Liberal Democrat Councillor Steve Delaney was elected Depute Provost.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] SNP Group Leader Alex Nicoll and Liberal Democrat Group Leader Ian Yuill became Co-Leaders of the Council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Effective April 2, 2026, Desmond Buchanan, Councillor for George Street/Harbour ward resigned.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The Returning Officer announced the By-Election will take place on Thursday, June 25th 2026.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Council meetings are held at Aberdeen Town House on Broad Street, which was built in 1874 and substantially extended in 1975, including a new council chamber.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The council's main offices are now in the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The council moved into the renovated former college building in 2011.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Before May 2007, councillors represented 43 single-member wards election on a first-past-the-post basis.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] On 3 May 2007, the single transferable vote system was used for the first time and multi-member wards were introduced, each ward electing three or four councillors.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] The Local Government Boundary Commission for Scotland completed its final recommendations for new wards for all the council areas of Scotland.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen is divided into 13 multi-member wards, electing a total of 45 councillors.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-city-council] This system was introduced as a result of the Local Governance (Scotland) Act 2004, and is designed to produce a form of proportional representation.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital has its origins in the a small facility established at Guestrow in 1870.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] It moved to Barrett's Close in 1893 and to Castle Street in 1900.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The move to a new building, which was designed by James Brown Nicol and built between 1934 and 1937, formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by Professor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] An ante-natal hospital was added in 1941 and the facility joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital progressed to stage two accreditation of the Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative in July 2011.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Construction of new hospital buildings - for The Baird Family Hospital and Anchor cancer centre - was delayed after costs escalated from £163m to £223m.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] In February 2020, forecast completion dates were 2022 and March 2023 respectively.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The Department of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, University of Aberdeen, is based at the hospital, which conducts a variety of research with an emphasis on obstetric epidemiology (including maternal mortality and morbidity), infertility and the prevention of cancer in women.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Aberdeen is also particularly known for its research into multiple pregnancy.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The associated **Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health** was set up in 1995 and is primarily a research unit, with consultative and teaching responsibilities.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Current work focuses on a number of themes in reproductive health research and methodological development in evaluation.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The centre is named after Sir Dugald Baird (1899–1986), Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen from 1937 to 1965.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:dugald-baird/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] 87) is an act of the Parliament of the United Kingdom that legalised abortion in Great Britain on certain grounds by registered practitioners, and regulated the tax-paid provision of such medical practices through the National Health Service (NHS).
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] The act made it lawful to have an abortion up to the 28th week if two registered medical practitioners believed in good faith that the continuance of the pregnancy would involve risk to the life of the pregnant woman, or harm her physical or mental health, or that of any of her family members.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] It did not extend to Northern Ireland until the implementation of the Abortion (Northern Ireland) Regulations 2020.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] In the latter two cases, the good faith opinion of two registered medical professionals is required.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] The bill was introduced by Liberal MP David Steel as a Private Member's Bill after he did well in the ballot for such bills in 1966, coming third.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] There had been six earlier attempts to change the law on abortion, starting with an earlier Private Member's Bill from the Labour MP Joseph Reeves in 1952.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] Labour peer Lewis Silkin had introduced legislation in 1965, but withdrew this once Steel had successfully introduced his motion to the Commons, with Steel's bill being based on Silkin's text.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] There had been a long-running campaign supporting the legalisation of abortion in the UK, led by the Abortion Law Reform Association, who had lobbied Steel to use his Private Member's Bill slot on the topic.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] The proposal was backed by the Labour government, who appointed the president of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists, Sir John Peel, to chair a medical advisory committee that reported in favour of passing the bill.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] Several members of the government were sympathetic to legalisation, including Roy Jenkins (Home Secretary), Kenneth Robinson (Minister of Health), Richard Crossman (Leader of the House), and John Silkin (Government Chief Whip).
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] After a further heated political and moral debate, the House of Commons passed it by a vote of 167 to 83 on 13 July 1967.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] The House of Lords granted it a second reading by a vote of 127 to 21 on 19 July, and approved it with minor changes on 23 October.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] On 25 October, the Commons voted 188–94 to agree with the amendments made by the Lords.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] The bill was enacted two days later, and came into force on 27 April 1968.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] Since 1967, members of Parliament have introduced a number of private member's bills to change the abortion law.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] The Lane Committee investigated the workings of the Act in 1974 and declared its support.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] Changes to the Abortion Act 1967 were introduced in Parliament through the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Act 1990.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] The time limits were lowered from 28 to 24 weeks for most cases on the grounds that medical technology had advanced sufficiently to justify the change.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] Restrictions were removed for late abortions in cases of risk to life, fetal abnormality, or grave physical and mental injury to the woman.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] Some Members of Parliament claimed not to have been aware of the vast change the decoupling of the Infant Life Preservation Act 1929 would have on the Abortion Act 1967, particularly in relation to the unborn disabled child.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] Politicians from the unionist and nationalist parties in Northern Ireland joined forces on 20 June 2000 to block any extension of the Abortion Act 1967 to Northern Ireland where terminations were only allowed on a restricted basis.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] There was widespread action across the country to oppose any attempts to restrict abortion access via the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Bill (now Act) in Parliament (Report Stage and Third Reading 22 October 2008).
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] MPs voted to retain the current legal limit of 24 weeks.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] Amendments proposing reductions to 22 weeks and 20 weeks were defeated by 304 to 233 votes and 332 to 190 votes respectively.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] A number of abortion rights amendments were proposed by Diane Abbott MP, Katy Clark MP and John McDonnell MP - including NC30 Amendment of the Abortion Act 1967: Application to Northern Ireland.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] However, it was reported that the Labour Government at the time asked MPs not to table these amendments (and at least until Third Reading) and then allegedly used parliamentary mechanisms in order to prevent a vote.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] Harriet Harman, in particular, was reported to have blocked the series of votes to liberalise Britain's abortion laws.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] In May 2017, the Labour Party under Jeremy Corbyn's leadership made a commitment to extend the Abortion Act 1967 to Northern Ireland.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] In June 2017, the UK Government revealed plans to provide some type of free abortion services in England for women from Northern Ireland in an attempt to head off a Conservative rebellion in a vote on the Queen's speech.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] The Northern Ireland (Executive Formation etc) Act 2019, enacted on 24 July 2019, extended the deadline for the restoration of the Executive to 21 October 2019.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-act-1967] On 21 October 2019, as a result of the Executive not being restored, sections 58 and 59 of the 1861 act were repealed, decriminalising abortion in Northern Ireland.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] When done legally in industrialized societies, induced abortion is one of the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Modern methods use medication or surgery for abortions.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The drug mifepristone (aka RU-486) in combination with prostaglandin appears to be as safe and effective as surgery during the first and second trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Self-managed medication abortion is highly effective and safe throughout the first trimester.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The most common surgical technique involves dilating the cervix and using a suction device.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Birth control, such as contraceptive pills or intrauterine devices, can be used immediately following an abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] When performed legally and safely on a woman who desires it, an induced abortion does not increase the risk of long-term mental or physical problems.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In contrast, unsafe abortions performed by unskilled individuals, with hazardous equipment, or in unsanitary facilities cause between 22,000 and 44,000 deaths and 6.9 million hospital admissions each year — responsible for between 5% and 13% of maternal deaths, especially in low-income countries.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization states that "access to legal, safe and comprehensive abortion care, including post-abortion care, is essential for the attainment of the highest possible level of sexual and reproductive health".
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Public health data show that making safe abortion legal and accessible reduces maternal deaths.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Around 73 million abortions are performed each year in the world, with about 45% done unsafely.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Abortion rates changed little between 2003 and 2008, before which they decreased for at least two decades as access to family planning and birth control increased.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] As of 2018, 37% of the world's women had access to legal abortions without limits as to reason.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Countries that permit abortions have different limits on how late in pregnancy abortion is allowed.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Abortion rates are similar between countries that restrict abortion and countries that broadly allow it, though this is partly because countries which restrict abortion tend to have higher unintended pregnancy rates.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Since 1973, there has been a global trend towards greater legal access to abortion, but there remains debate with regard to moral, religious, ethical, and legal issues.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Those who oppose abortion often argue that an embryo or fetus is a person with a right to life, and thus equate abortion with murder.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Those who support abortion's legality often argue that it is a woman's reproductive right.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Others favor legal and accessible abortion as a public health measure.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Abortion laws and views of the procedure are different around the world.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In some countries abortion is legal and women have the right to make the choice about abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In some areas, abortion is legal only in specific cases such as rape, incest, fetal defects, poverty, and risk to a woman's health.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Historically, abortions have been attempted using herbal medicines, sharp tools, forceful massage, or other traditional methods.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] An induced abortion is a medical procedure to end a pregnancy.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In present-day English, the term *abortion*, when used without further qualification, generally refers to induced abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A pregnancy can be intentionally aborted in several ways.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The abortion method depends upon the gestational age of the embryo or fetus, which gains mass as the pregnancy progresses.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Abortion laws, regional availability, and the personal preference of the woman and her doctor may inform the woman's choice of a specific abortion procedure.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Abortions can be characterized as either therapeutic or elective.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] When an abortion is performed for medical reasons, the procedure is referred to as a therapeutic abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] An abortion is referred to as elective or voluntary when it is performed at the request of the woman for non-medical reasons.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Confusion sometimes arises over the term *elective* because "elective surgery" generally refers to all scheduled surgery, whether medically necessary or not.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] About one in five pregnancies worldwide ends with an induced abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Most abortions result from unintended pregnancies.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In the United Kingdom, 1 to 2% of abortions are done because of genetic problems in the fetus.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Miscarriage, also known as spontaneous abortion, is the unintentional expulsion of an embryo or fetus before the 24th week of gestation.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A pregnancy that ends before 37 weeks of gestation resulting in a live-born infant is a "premature birth" or a "preterm birth".
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] When a fetus dies in utero after viability, or during delivery, it is usually termed "stillborn".
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Premature births and stillbirths are generally not considered to be miscarriages, although usage of these terms can sometimes overlap.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Studies of pregnant women in the US and China have shown that between 40% and 60% of embryos do not progress to birth.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The vast majority of miscarriages occur before the woman is aware that she is pregnant, and many pregnancies spontaneously abort before medical practitioners can detect an embryo.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Between 15% and 30% of known pregnancies end in clinically apparent miscarriage, depending upon the age and health of the pregnant woman.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] 80% of these spontaneous abortions happen in the first trimester.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The most common cause of spontaneous abortion during the first trimester is chromosomal abnormalities of the embryo or fetus, accounting for at least 50% of sampled early pregnancy losses.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Other causes include vascular disease (such as lupus), diabetes, other hormonal problems, infection, and abnormalities of the uterus.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Advancing maternal age and a woman's history of previous spontaneous abortions are the two leading factors associated with a greater risk of spontaneous abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A spontaneous abortion can also be caused by accidental trauma; intentional trauma or stress to cause miscarriage is considered induced abortion or feticide.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] may determine which abortion methods are practiced.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Medical abortions are those induced by abortifacient pharmaceuticals.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Medical abortion became an alternative method of abortion with the availability of prostaglandin analogs in the 1970s and the antiprogestogen mifepristone (also known as RU-486) in the 1980s.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimens work faster and are more effective at later gestational ages than methotrexate–misoprostol combination regimens, and combination regimens are more effective than misoprostol alone, particularly in the second trimester.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Medical abortion regimens involving mifepristone followed by misoprostol in the cheek between 24 and 48 hours later are effective when performed before 70 days' gestation.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In very early abortions, up to 7 weeks gestation, medical abortion using a mifepristone–misoprostol combination regimen is considered to be more effective than surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration), especially when clinical practice does not include detailed inspection of aspirated tissue.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Early medical abortion regimens using mifepristone, followed 24–48 hours later by buccal or vaginal misoprostol are 98% effective up to 9 weeks gestational age; from 9 to 10 weeks efficacy decreases modestly to 94%.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] If medical abortion fails, surgical abortion must be used to complete the procedure.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Early medical abortions account for the majority of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in Britain, France, Switzerland, United States, and the Nordic countries.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A 2020 Cochrane Systematic Review concluded that providing women with medications to take home to complete the second stage of the procedure for an early medical abortion results in an effective abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Further research is required to determine if self-administered medical abortion is as safe as provider-administered medical abortion, where a health care professional is present to help manage the medical abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Safely permitting women to self-administer abortion medication has the potential to improve access to abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The review also noted a research gap concerning methods to support women who take medication at home for a self-administered abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Up to 15 weeks' gestation, suction-aspiration or vacuum aspiration are the most common surgical methods of induced abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] *Manual vacuum aspiration* (MVA) consists of removing the fetus or embryo, placenta, and membranes by suction using a manual syringe, while *electric vacuum aspiration* (EVA) uses an electric pump.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Both techniques can be used very early in pregnancy.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] MVA can be used up to 14 weeks but is more often used earlier in the U.S.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] MVA, also known as "mini-suction" and "menstrual extraction", or EVA can be used in very early pregnancy when cervical dilation may not be required.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Dilation and curettage (D&C) refers to opening the cervix (dilation) and removing tissue (curettage) via suction or sharp instruments.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] D&C is a standard gynecological procedure performed for a variety of reasons, including examination of the uterine lining for possible malignancy, investigation of abnormal bleeding, and abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization recommends *sharp curettage* only when suction aspiration is unavailable.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Dilation and evacuation (D&E), used after 12 to 16 weeks, consists of opening the cervix and removing pregnancy tissue and fetal parts with suction and forceps.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] D&E is performed vaginally and does not require an incision.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Intact dilation and extraction (D&X) refers to a variant of D&E sometimes used after 18 to 20 weeks when removal of an intact fetus improves surgical safety or for other reasons.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Abortion may also be performed surgically by hysterotomy or gravid hysterectomy.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy abortion is a procedure similar to a caesarean section and is performed under general anesthesia.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] It requires a smaller incision than a caesarean section and can be used during later stages of pregnancy.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Gravid hysterectomy refers to removal of the whole uterus while still containing the pregnancy.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Hysterotomy and hysterectomy are associated with much higher rates of maternal morbidity and mortality than D&E or induction abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] First trimester procedures can generally be performed using local anesthesia, while second trimester methods may require deep sedation or general anesthesia.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In places lacking the necessary medical skill for dilation and extraction, or when preferred by practitioners, an abortion can be induced by first inducing labor and then inducing fetal demise if necessary.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] This is sometimes called "induced miscarriage".
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] This procedure may be performed from 13 weeks gestation to the third trimester.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Although it is very uncommon in the United States, more than 80% of induced abortions throughout the second trimester are labor-induced abortions in Sweden and other nearby countries.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Only limited data are available comparing labor-induced abortion with the dilation and extraction method.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Unlike D&E, labor-induced abortions after 18 weeks may be complicated by the occurrence of brief fetal survival, which may be legally characterized as live birth.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] For this reason, labor-induced abortion is legally risky in the United States.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Historically, a number of herbs reputed to possess abortifacient properties have been used in folk medicine.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Such herbs include tansy, pennyroyal, black cohosh, and the now-extinct silphium.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In 1978, one woman in Colorado died and another developed organ damage when they attempted to terminate their pregnancies by taking pennyroyal oil.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Because the indiscriminant use of herbs as abortifacients can cause serious—even lethal—side effects, such as multiple organ failure, such use is not recommended by physicians.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Abortion is sometimes attempted by causing trauma to the abdomen.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The degree of force, if severe, can cause serious internal injuries without necessarily succeeding in inducing miscarriage.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In Southeast Asia, there is an ancient tradition of attempting abortion through forceful abdominal massage.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] One of the bas reliefs decorating the temple of Angkor Wat in Cambodia depicts a demon performing such an abortion upon a woman who had been sent to the underworld.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Reported methods of unsafe, self-induced abortion include misuse of misoprostol and insertion of non-surgical implements such as knitting needles and clothes hangers into the uterus.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] These and other methods to terminate pregnancy may be called "induced miscarriage".
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Such methods are rarely used in countries where surgical abortion is legal and available.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The health risks of abortion depend principally on how, and under what conditions, the procedure is performed.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization (WHO) defines unsafe abortions as a procedure for terminating an unintended pregnancy carried out either by persons lacking the necessary skills or in an environment that does not conform to minimal medical standards, or both.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Legal abortions performed in the developed world are among the safest procedures in medicine.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] According to a 2012 study in *Obstetrics & Gynecology*, in the United States the risk of maternal mortality is 14 times lower after induced abortion than after childbirth.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The CDC estimated in 2019 that US pregnancy-related mortality was 17.2 maternal deaths per 100,000 live births, while the US abortion mortality rate was 0.43 maternal deaths per 100,000 procedures.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In the UK, guidelines of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists state that "Women should be advised that abortion is generally safer than continuing a pregnancy to term." Worldwide, on average, abortion is safer than carrying a pregnancy to term.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In the US from 2000 to 2009, abortion had a mortality rate lower than plastic surgery, lower or similar to running a marathon, and about equivalent to traveling 760 miles (1,220 km) in a passenger car.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Outpatient abortion is as safe from 64 to 70 days' gestation as it before 63 days.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A 2019 study indicated that five years after seeking abortion services, women who gave birth after being denied an abortion reported worse health than women who had either first or second trimester abortions.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] There is little difference in terms of safety and efficacy between medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol and surgical abortion (vacuum aspiration) in early first trimester abortions up to 10 weeks gestation.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Medical abortion using the prostaglandin analog misoprostol alone is less effective and more painful than medical abortion using a combined regimen of mifepristone and misoprostol or surgical abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Vacuum aspiration in the first trimester is the safest method of surgical abortion, and can be performed in a primary care office, abortion clinic, or hospital.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Complications, which are rare, can include uterine perforation, pelvic infection, and retained products of conception requiring a second procedure to evacuate.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Infections account for one-third of abortion-related deaths in the United States.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The rate of complications of vacuum aspiration abortion in the first trimester is similar regardless of whether the procedure is performed in a hospital, surgical center, or office.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Preventive antibiotics (such as doxycycline or metronidazole) are typically given before abortion procedures, as they are believed to substantially reduce the risk of postoperative uterine infection; however, antibiotics are not routinely given with abortion pills.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The rate of failed procedures does not appear to vary significantly depending on whether the abortion is performed by a doctor or a mid-level practitioner.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Complications after second trimester abortion are similar to those after first trimester abortion, and depend somewhat on the method chosen.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The risk of death from abortion approaches roughly half the risk of death from childbirth the farther along a woman is in pregnancy; from one in a million before 9 weeks gestation to nearly one in ten thousand at 21 weeks or more (as measured from the last menstrual period).
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] It appears that having had a prior surgical uterine evacuation (whether because of induced abortion or treatment of miscarriage) correlates with a small increase in the risk of preterm birth in future pregnancies.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The studies supporting this did not control for factors not related to abortion or miscarriage, and hence the causes of this correlation have not been determined, although multiple possibilities have been suggested.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Current evidence finds no relationship between most induced abortions and mental health problems other than those expected for any unwanted pregnancy.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Some older reviews concluded that abortion was associated with an increased risk of psychological problems; however, later reviews of the medical literature found that previous reviews did not use an appropriate control group.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] When a control group is utilized, receiving abortion is not associated with adverse psychological outcomes.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] However, women seeking abortion who are denied access to abortion have an increase in anxiety after the denial.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Although some studies show negative mental-health outcomes in women who choose abortions after the first trimester because of fetal abnormalities, more rigorous research would be needed to show this conclusively.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Some proposed negative psychological effects of abortion have been referred to by anti-abortion advocates as a separate condition called "post-abortion syndrome", but this is not recognized by medical or psychological professionals in the United States.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A 2020 long term-study among US women found that about 99% of women felt that they made the right decision five years after they had an abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Relief was the primary emotion with few women feeling sadness or guilt.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Social stigma was a main factor predicting negative emotions and regret years later.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Some purported risks of abortion are promoted primarily by anti-abortion groups, but lack scientific support.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] For example, the question of a link between induced abortion and breast cancer has been investigated extensively.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Major medical and scientific bodies (including the WHO, National Cancer Institute, American Cancer Society, Royal College of OBGYN and American Congress of OBGYN) have concluded that abortion does not cause breast cancer.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In the past even illegality has not automatically meant that the abortions were unsafe.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A 1940s American physician spoke of his pride in having performed 13,844 illegal abortions without any fatalities.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In 1870s New York City, the abortionist/midwife Madame Restell (Anna Trow Lohman) is said to have lost very few women among her more than 100,000 patients—a lower mortality rate than the childbirth mortality rate at the time.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In 1936, obstetrics and gynecology professor Frederick J.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Women seeking an abortion may use unsafe methods, especially when abortion is legally restricted.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] They may attempt self-induced abortion or seek the help of a person without proper medical training or facilities.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] This can lead to severe complications, such as incomplete abortion, sepsis, hemorrhage, and damage to internal organs.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are a major cause of injury and death among women worldwide.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Although data are imprecise, it is estimated that approximately 20 million unsafe abortions are performed annually, with 97% taking place in developing countries.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Unsafe abortions are believed to result in millions of injuries.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Estimates of deaths vary according to methodology, and have ranged from 37,000 to 70,000 in the past decade; deaths from unsafe abortion account for around 13% of all maternal deaths.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The World Health Organization believes that mortality has fallen since the 1990s.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] To reduce the number of unsafe abortions, public health organizations have generally advocated emphasizing the legalization of abortion, training of medical personnel, and ensuring access to reproductive-health services.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A major factor in whether abortions are performed safely or not is the legal standing of abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Countries with restrictive abortion laws have higher rates of unsafe abortion and similar overall abortion rates compared to countries where abortion is legal and available.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] For example, the 1996 legalization of abortion in South Africa led to an immediate reduction in abortion-related complications, with abortion-related deaths dropping by more than 90%.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Similar reductions in maternal mortality have been observed after other countries have liberalized their abortion laws, such as Romania and Nepal.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A 2011 study concluded that in the United States, some state-level anti-abortion laws are correlated with lower rates of abortion in that state.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The analysis, however, did not take into account travel to other states without such laws to obtain an abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In addition, a lack of access to effective contraception contributes to unsafe abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] It has been estimated that the incidence of unsafe abortion could be reduced by up to 75% (from 20 million to 5 million annually) if modern family planning and maternal health services were readily available globally.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Rates of such abortions may be difficult to measure because they can be reported variously as miscarriage, "induced miscarriage", "menstrual regulation", "mini-abortion", and "regulation of a delayed/suspended menstruation".
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Forty percent of the world's women are able to access therapeutic and elective abortions within gestational limits, while an additional 35 percent have access to legal abortion if they meet certain physical, mental, or socioeconomic criteria.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] While maternal mortality seldom results from safe abortions, unsafe abortions result in 70,000 deaths and 5 million disabilities per year.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Complications of unsafe abortion account for approximately an eighth of maternal mortalities worldwide, though this varies by region.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Secondary infertility caused by an unsafe abortion affects an estimated 24 million women.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The rate of unsafe abortions has increased from 44% to 49% between 1995 and 2008.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Health education, access to family planning, and improvements in health care during and after abortion have been proposed to address consequences of unsafe abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In many places, where abortion is illegal or carries a heavy social stigma, medical reporting of abortion is not reliable.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] For this reason, estimates of the incidence of abortion must be made without determining certainty related to standard error.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The number of abortions performed worldwide was characterized as stable in the early 2000s, with 41.6 million having been performed in 2003 and 43.8 million having been performed in 2008.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The abortion rate worldwide was 28 per 1000 women per year, though it was 24 per 1000 women per year for developed countries and 29 per 1000 women per year for developing countries.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The same 2012 study indicated that in 2008, the estimated abortion percentage of known pregnancies was at 21% worldwide, with 26% in developed countries and 20% in developing countries.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] On average, the incidence of abortion is similar in countries with restrictive abortion laws and those with more liberal access to abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Restrictive abortion laws are associated with increases in the percentage of abortions performed unsafely.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The rate of legal, induced abortion varies extensively worldwide.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] According to the report of employees of Guttmacher Institute it ranged from 7 per 1000 women per year (Germany and Switzerland) to 30 per 1000 women per year (Estonia) in countries with complete statistics in 2008.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The proportion of pregnancies that ended in induced abortion ranged from about 10% (Israel, the Netherlands and Switzerland) to 30% (Estonia) in the same group, though it might be as high as 36% in Hungary and Romania, whose statistics were deemed incomplete.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] An American study in 2002 concluded that about half of women having abortions were using a form of contraception at the time of becoming pregnant.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Inconsistent use was reported by half of those using condoms and three-quarters of those using the birth control pill; 42% of those using condoms reported failure through slipping or breakage.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Of the other half of women, who were not using contraception at the time of becoming pregnant, the vast majority had used contraception at some point in the past, indicating some level of dissatisfaction with the contraceptive options available to them.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Indeed, 32% of these contraceptive nonusers cited concerns about contraceptive methods as their reason for nonuse, and a more recent study found similar results.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Taken together, these statistics suggest that new contraceptive methods, such as non-hormonal contraceptives or male contraceptives, could reduce unintended pregnancy and abortion rates.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute has found that "most abortions in the United States are obtained by minority women" because minority women "have much higher rates of unintended pregnancy".
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] in England and Wales during 2019 (left).
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Abortion in the United States by gestational age, 2016 (right).
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Abortion rates vary depending on the stage of pregnancy and the method practiced.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] 91% of these were classified as having been done by "curettage" (suction-aspiration, dilation and curettage, dilation and evacuation), 8% by "medical" means (mifepristone), >1% by "intrauterine instillation" (saline or prostaglandin), and 1% by "other" (including hysterotomy and hysterectomy).
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] According to the CDC, due to data collection difficulties the data must be viewed as tentative and some fetal deaths reported beyond 20 weeks may be natural deaths erroneously classified as abortions if the removal of the dead fetus is accomplished by the same procedure as an induced abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The Guttmacher Institute estimated there were 2,200 intact dilation and extraction procedures in the US during 2000; this accounts for <0.2% of the total number of abortions performed that year.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Similarly, in England and Wales in 2006, 89% of terminations occurred at or under 12 weeks, 9% between 13 and 19 weeks, and 2% at or over 20 weeks.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] 64% of those reported were by vacuum aspiration, 6% by D&E, and 30% were medical.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] There are more second trimester abortions in developing countries such as China, India and Vietnam than in developed countries.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] There are both medical and non-medical reasons to have an abortion later in pregnancy (after 20 weeks).
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A study was conducted from 2008 to 2010 at the University of California San Francisco where more than 440 women were asked about why they experienced delays in obtaining abortion care, if there were any.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] This study found that almost half of individuals who obtained an abortion after 20 weeks did not suspect that they were pregnant until later in their pregnancy.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Other barriers to abortion care found in the study included lack of information about where to access an abortion, difficulties with transportation, lack of insurance coverage, and inability to pay for the abortion procedure.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Medical reasons for seeking an abortion later in pregnancy include fetal anomalies and health risk to the pregnant person.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] There are prenatal tests that can diagnose Down Syndrome or cystic fibrosis as early as 10 weeks into gestation, but structural fetal anomalies are often detected much later in pregnancy.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A proportion of structural fetal anomalies are lethal, which means that the fetus will almost certainly die before or shortly after birth.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Life-threatening conditions may also develop later in pregnancy, such as early severe preeclampsia, newly diagnosed cancer in need of urgent treatment, and intrauterine infection (chorioamnionitis), which often occurs along with premature rupture of the amniotic sac (PPROM).
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] If serious medical conditions such as these arise before the fetus is viable, the person carrying the pregnancy may pursue an abortion to preserve their own health.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The reasons why women have abortions are diverse and vary across the world.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Some of the reasons may include an inability to afford a child, domestic violence, lack of support, feeling they are too young, and the wish to complete education or advance a career.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Additional reasons include not being able or willing to raise a child conceived as a result of rape or incest.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Some abortions are undergone as the result of societal pressures.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] These factors can sometimes result in compulsory abortion or sex-selective abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In cultures where there is a preference for male children, some women have sex selective abortions, which have partially replaced the earlier practice of female infanticide.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Some abortions are performed due to concerns over maternal health.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In 1990s, women cited maternal health as their main motivating factor in about a third of abortions in three of 27 countries analyzed.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In seven additional countries, about 7% of abortions were maternal health related.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In the U.S., the Supreme Court decisions in *Roe v.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Bolton*: "ruled that the state's interest in the life of the fetus became compelling only at the point of viability, defined as the point at which the fetus can survive independently of its mother.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Even after the point of viability, the state cannot favor the life of the fetus over the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Under the right of privacy, physicians must be free to use their "medical judgment for the preservation of the life or health of the mother".
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] On the same day that the Court decided Roe, it also decided Doe v.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Bolton, in which the Court defined health very broadly: "The medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The rate of cancer during pregnancy is 0.02–1%, and in many cases, cancer of the mother leads to consideration of abortion to protect the life of the mother, or in response to the potential damage that may occur to the fetus during treatment.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] This is particularly true for cervical cancer, the most common type of which occurs in 1 of every 2,000–13,000 pregnancies, for which initiation of treatment "cannot co-exist with preservation of fetal life (unless neoadjuvant chemotherapy is chosen)".
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Very early stage cervical cancers (I and IIa) may be treated by radical hysterectomy and pelvic lymph node dissection, radiation therapy, or both, while later stages are treated by radiotherapy.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Chemotherapy may be used simultaneously.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Treatment of breast cancer during pregnancy also involves fetal considerations, because lumpectomy is discouraged in favor of modified radical mastectomy unless late-term pregnancy allows follow-up radiation therapy to be administered after the birth.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Exposure to a single chemotherapy drug is estimated to cause a 7.5–17% risk of teratogenic effects on the fetus, with higher risks for multiple drug treatments.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Treatment with more than 40 Gy of radiation usually causes spontaneous abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Exposure to much lower doses during the first trimester, especially 8 to 15 weeks of development, can cause intellectual disability or microcephaly, and exposure at this or subsequent stages can cause reduced intrauterine growth and birth weight.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Exposures above 0.005–0.025 Gy cause a dose-dependent reduction in IQ.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] It is possible to greatly reduce exposure to radiation with abdominal shielding, depending on how far the area to be irradiated is from the fetus.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The process of birth itself may also put the mother at risk.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Congenital disorders, revealed by prenatal screening, motivate some women to seek abortions.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Health outcomes of preterm births include a significant probability of long-term neurodevelopmental impairment before gestational age of 29 weeks, with a higher probability with decreasing gestational age.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In the United States, public opinion shifted after television personality Sherri Finkbine's was exposed to thalidomide, a teratogen, in her fifth month of pregnancy.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Unable to obtain a legal abortion in the United States, Finkbine traveled to Sweden.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] From 1962 to 1965, an outbreak of German measles left 15,000 babies with severe birth defects.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In 1967, the American Medical Association publicly supported liberalization of abortion laws.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A National Opinion Research Center poll in 1965 showed 73% supported abortion when the mother's life was at risk, 57% when birth defects were present and 59% for pregnancies resulting from rape or incest.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Since ancient times, abortions have been done using a number of methods, including herbal medicines acting as abortifacients, sharp tools through the use of force, or through other traditional medicine methods.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Induced abortion has a long history and can be traced back to civilizations as varied as ancient China (abortifacient knowledge is often attributed to the mythological ruler Shennong), ancient India since its Vedic age, ancient Egypt with its Ebers Papyrus (c.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] 1550 BCE), and the Roman Empire in the time of Juvenal (c.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] One of the earliest known artistic representations of abortion is in a bas relief at Angkor Wat (c.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Found in a series of friezes that represent judgment after death in Hindu and Buddhist culture, it depicts the technique of abdominal abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In *Politics* (350 BCE), Aristotle condemned infanticide as a means of population control.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] He preferred abortion in such cases, with the restriction that it "must be practised on it before it has developed sensation and life; for the line between lawful and unlawful abortion will be marked by the fact of having sensation and being alive".
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Abortion has been a fairly common practice, and was not always illegal or controversial until the 19th century.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In Europe and North America, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century; the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Other medical practitioners in addition to some physicians advertised their services, and they were not widely regulated until the 19th century when the practice, sometimes called *restellism*, was banned in both the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Some 19th-century physicians, argued for anti-abortion laws on racist and misogynist as well as moral grounds.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Church groups were also highly influential in anti-abortion movements, and religious groups more so since the 20th century.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Some of the early anti-abortion laws punished only the doctor or abortionist, and while women could be criminally tried for a self-induced abortion, they were rarely prosecuted in general.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Some maintain that in the 19th century early abortions under the hygienic conditions in which midwives usually worked were relatively safe.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Several scholars argue that, despite improved medical procedures, the period from the 1930s until the 1970s saw more zealous enforcement of anti-abortion laws, alongside an increasing control of abortion providers by organized crime.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In 1920, Soviet Russia became the first country to legalize abortion after Lenin insisted that no woman be forced to give birth.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Abortion was then legalized in some form in Iceland (1935), Sweden (1938), Nazi Germany (1935) and Japan (1948) Beginning in the second half of the 20th century, abortion was legalized in a greater number of countries.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In the Catholic Church, opinion was divided on how serious abortion was in comparison with such acts as contraception and oral or anal sex.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The Catholic Church did not begin vigorously opposing abortion until the 19th century.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] As early as ~100 CE, the *Didache* taught that abortion was sinful.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Several historians argue that prior to the 19th century most Catholic authors did not regard termination of pregnancy before quickening or ensoulment as an abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] 1585–1590) was the first Pope to institute a Church policy labeling all abortion as homicide and condemning abortion regardless of the stage of pregnancy.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Sixtus V's pronouncement was reversed in 1591 by Pope Gregory XIV.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In the recodification of 1917 Code of Canon Law, *Apostolicae Sedis* was strengthened, in part to remove a possible reading that excluded excommunication of the mother.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Statements made in the *Catechism of the Catholic Church*, the codified summary of the Church's teachings, considers abortion from the moment of conception as homicide and called for the end of legal abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Denominations that support abortion rights with some limits include the United Methodist Church, Episcopal Church, Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and Presbyterian Church USA.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A 2014 Guttmacher survey of abortion patients in the United States found that many reported a religious affiliation: 24% were Catholic while 30% were Protestant.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A 1995 survey reported that Catholic women are as likely as the general population to terminate a pregnancy, Protestants are less likely to do so, and evangelical Christians are the least likely to do so.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] A 2019 Pew Research Center study found that most Christian denominations were against overturning *Roe v.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Wade,* which in the United States legalized abortion, at around 70%, except White Evangelicals at 35%.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In Judaism, the fetus is not considered to have a human soul until it is safely outside of the woman, is viable, and has taken its first breath.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] The fetus is considered valuable property of the woman and not a human life while in the womb (Exodus 21:22-23).
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] While Judaism encourages people to be fruitful and multiply by having children, abortion is allowed and is deemed necessary when a pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Several religions, including Judaism, which disagree that human life begins at conception, support the legality of abortion on religious freedom grounds.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] In Islam, abortion is traditionally permitted until a point in time when Muslims believe the soul enters the fetus, considered by various theologians to be at conception, 40 days after conception, 120 days after conception, or at quickening.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Abortion is largely heavily restricted or forbidden in areas of high Islamic faith such as the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Hindu views on abortion are diverse and lack a single authoritative position, shaped by principles like ahimsa (non-violence), karma, and reincarnation, which typically regard it as morally wrong for interrupting the soul's cycle.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Scriptures often equate abortion to grave sins, with the fetus considered ensouled from conception or early gestation.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] However, it may be ethically permissible to save the mother's life or in cases of severe fetal abnormalities, prioritizing lesser harm.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p01] Modern opinions differ regionally: In India, a majority view abortion as generally illegal, while in the US, most Hindus support legal access in all or most cases.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Induced abortion has long been the source of considerable debate.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Ethical, moral, philosophical, biological, religious and legal issues surrounding abortion are related to value systems.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Opinions of abortion may be about fetal rights, governmental authority, and women's rights.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] In both public and private debate, arguments presented in favor of or against abortion access focus on either the moral permissibility of an induced abortion, or the justification of laws permitting or restricting abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] The World Medical Association Declaration on Therapeutic Abortion notes, "circumstances bringing the interests of a mother into conflict with the interests of her unborn child create a dilemma and raise the question as to whether or not the pregnancy should be deliberately terminated".
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Abortion debates, especially pertaining to abortion laws, are often spearheaded by groups advocating one of these two positions.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Groups who favor greater legal restrictions on abortion, including complete prohibition, most often describe themselves as "pro-life" while groups who are against such legal restrictions describe themselves as "pro-choice".
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] The median voters stance on abortion varies by jurisdiction and can result in swing votes.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Current laws pertaining to abortion are diverse.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Religious, moral, and cultural factors continue to influence abortion laws throughout the world.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] The right to life, the right to liberty, the right to security of person, and the right to reproductive health are major issues of human rights that sometimes constitute the basis for the existence or absence of abortion laws.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] In jurisdictions where abortion is legal, certain requirements must often be met before a woman may obtain a legal abortion (an abortion performed without the woman's consent is considered feticide and is generally illegal).
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] These requirements usually depend on the age of the fetus, often using a trimester-based system to regulate the window of legality, or as in the U.S., on a doctor's evaluation of the fetus' viability.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Some jurisdictions require a waiting period before the procedure, prescribe the distribution of information on fetal development, or require that parents be contacted if their minor daughter requests an abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Many restrictions are waived in emergency situations.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] China, which has ended their one-child policy, and now has a three-child policy, has at times incorporated mandatory abortions as part of their population control strategy.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Other jurisdictions ban abortion almost entirely.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Many, but not all, of these allow legal abortions in a variety of circumstances.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] These circumstances vary based on jurisdiction, but may include whether the pregnancy is a result of rape or incest, the fetus' development is impaired, the woman's physical or mental well-being is endangered, or socioeconomic considerations make childbirth a hardship.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] In countries where abortion is banned entirely, such as Nicaragua, medical authorities have recorded rises in maternal death directly and indirectly due to pregnancy as well as deaths due to doctors' fears of prosecution if they treat other gynecological emergencies.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Some countries, such as Bangladesh, that nominally ban abortion, may also support clinics that perform abortions under the guise of menstrual hygiene.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] This is also a terminology in traditional medicine.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] In places where abortion is illegal or carries heavy social stigma, pregnant women may engage in medical tourism and travel to countries where they can terminate their pregnancies.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Women on Waves has provided medication abortion and education on a ship in international waters off the coast of countries with restrictive abortion laws.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Women without the means to travel can resort to providers of illegal abortions or attempt to perform an abortion by themselves.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Sonography and amniocentesis allow parents to determine sex before childbirth.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] The development of this technology has led to sex-selective abortion, or the termination of a fetus based on its sex.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] The selective termination of a female fetus is most common.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Sex-selective abortion is partially responsible for the noticeable disparities between the birth rates of male and female children in some countries.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] The preference for male children is reported in many areas of Asia, and abortion used to limit female births has been reported in Taiwan, South Korea, India, and China.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] This deviation from the standard birth rates of males and females occurs despite the fact that the country in question may have officially banned sex-selective abortion or even sex-screening.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Many countries have taken legislative steps to reduce the incidence of sex-selective abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] At the International Conference on Population and Development in 1994 over 180 states agreed to eliminate "all forms of discrimination against the girl child and the root causes of son preference", conditions also condemned by a PACE resolution in 2011.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] On the other hand, measures to reduce gender inequality can reduce the prevalence of such abortions without attendant negative consequences.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Abortion providers and facilities have been subjected to violence, including murder, assault, arson, and bombing.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Some scholars consider anti-abortion violence to be within the definition of terrorism, a view shared by some governments.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] In the U.S. and Canada, over 8,000 incidents of violence, trespassing, and death threats have been recorded by providers since 1977, including over 200 bombings/arsons and hundreds of assaults.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Abortion clinics have also been targeted by acid attacks, invasions, and vandalism The majority of abortion opponents have not been involved in violent acts.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Physicians and other abortion clinic staff have been murdered by abortion opponents.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] In the United States, at least four physicians have been murdered in connection with their work at abortion clinics, including David Gunn (1993), John Britton (1994), Barnett Slepian (1998), and George Tiller (2009).
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] In Canada, gynecologist Garson Romalis survived murder attempts in both 1994 and 2000.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Besides physicians, killings have targeted other clinic staff, such as John Salvi's 1994 murder of two receptionists in Massachusetts clinic and Peter Knight's 2001 murder of a security guard in a Melbourne clinic.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Notable perpetrators of anti-abortion violence include Eric Rudolph, Scott Roeder, Shelley Shannon, and Paul Hill, the first person to be executed in the United States for murdering an abortion provider.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Some countries have laws to protecting access to abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Such laws prevent abortion opponents from interfering with access to legal abortion services.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] For example, the American Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act bars the use of threats or violence to interfere with abortion access.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Abortion access laws may also establish safe access zones around abortion clinics, with limits on protests and enhanced penalties for anti-abortion violence.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Psychological pressure may also be used to limit abortion access.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Some protestors record women entering clinics on camera.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Spontaneous abortion occurs in various animals.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] For example, in sheep it may be caused by stress or physical exertion, such as crowding through doors or being chased by dogs.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] In cows, abortion may be caused by contagious disease, such as brucellosis or *Campylobacter*, but can often be controlled by vaccination.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Eating pine needles can also induce abortions in cows.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Several plants, including broomweed, skunk cabbage, poison hemlock, and tree tobacco, are known to cause fetal deformities and abortion in cattle, and in sheep and goats.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] In horses, a fetus may be aborted or resorbed if it has lethal white syndrome.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Foal embryos that are homozygous for the dominant white gene (WW) are theorized to also be aborted or resorbed before birth.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] In many species of sharks and rays, stress-induced abortions occur frequently upon capture.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Viral infection can cause abortion in dogs.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Cats can experience spontaneous abortion for many reasons, including hormonal imbalance.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] A combined abortion and spaying are performed on pregnant cats, especially in trap–neuter–return programs, to prevent unwanted kittens from being born.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Female rodents may terminate a pregnancy when exposed to the smell of a male not responsible for the pregnancy, known as the Bruce effect.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Abortion may also be induced in animals, in the context of animal husbandry.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] For example, abortion may be induced in mares that have been mated improperly, or that have been purchased by owners who did not realize the mares were pregnant, or that are pregnant with twin foals.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Feticide can occur in horses and zebras due to male harassment of pregnant mares or forced copulation, although the frequency in the wild has been questioned.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-p02] Male gray langur monkeys may attack females following male takeover, causing miscarriage.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] The "Abortion Law Reform Association" was founded in the United Kingdom in 1936 by Janet Chance, Alice Jenkins, Joan Malleson and Stella Browne.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] Its intention was to change attitudes and the law to allow access to abortion in the United Kingdom.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] Janet Chance created the funding and the marketing whilst Alice Brook Jenkins was the honorary secretary.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] Jenkins created a network of supporters.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] At the end of their first year they had 35 new members, and by 1939 they had almost 400.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] The membership were gathered from the working class using labour groups and women's branches of the co-operative movement.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] The ALRA was very active between 1936 and 1939 sending speakers around the country to talk about Labour and Equal Citizenship and attempted to have letters and articles published in newspapers.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] They were in the frame when a member of the ALRA's Medico-Legal Committee received the case of a fourteen-year-old girl who had been raped, and she received a termination of this pregnancy from Dr.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] Joan Malleson, a progenitor of the ALRA.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] Alice Jenkins wrote an important book titled "Law For The Rich" which was published in 1960.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] Her book drew attention to the double standards that faced women with unwanted pregnancies.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] Abortion was nominally illegal so many women had to give birth to unplanned children, however rich women could persuade their private doctors that their mental health was at risk.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] The doctors were then able to carry out an abortion that was denied to most women in Britain.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] During the 1970s and 1980s there were several proposed amendment bills against the Abortion Act 1967, so in defense of the Abortion Act 1967, the National Abortion Campaign (NAC) was formed in 1975.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] Vera Houghton became the chair of the ALRA in 1963 and over the next seven years she led the organisation.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] The ALRA's turning point was to gain the support of the Liberal Party MP David Steel, who placed a private members bill through the House of Commons to reform the laws of abortion, choosing this issue over calls to instead amend the law on plumbers or the rights of homosexuals.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] He cites Alice Jenkins' argument in her book "Law For The Rich" as being pivotal in his decision.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] Steele put forward a private members bill that was backed by the government and it resulted in the 1967 Abortion Act.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] In 1974 the ''Working Women's Charter" was developed by activists from the U.K.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] Women's Liberation and trade union movement.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] The charter was an attempt to bridge the gap between women's economic and social requirements, and included equal pay, an end to the glass ceiling, free contraception and access to abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] In 1975, the Scottish politician James White introduced a bill in parliament to make abortion more difficult.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] A demonstration was arranged to protest at moves to restrict the then legal access to abortion.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] This demonstration led to the formation of National Abortion Campaign.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] Abortion Rights was formed in 2003 by the merger of the Abortion Law Reform Association (ALRA) and the National Abortion Campaign (NAC).
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] The organisation is led by Anne Quesnay.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-rights-organisation] In 2016, abortion law was devolved to the Scottish Parliament in the Scotland Act 2016.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-support-network] The **Abortion Support Network** is a UK charity and abortion fund which provides financial assistance, accommodation and consultation to people in Europe who are seeking an abortion abroad.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-support-network] The charity was founded in 2009 by Mara Clarke.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-support-network] In 2017 as part of a coalition, ASN made a submission to the Citizens' Assembly.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-support-network] That same year, ASN fundraised and provided over £73,000 (€84,000) worth of grants for all associated expenses of obtaining an abortion, including travel.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-support-network] The team of volunteers fielded 1,009 phone calls (685 from Ireland) providing free advice.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-support-network] In 2019, in partnership with five organisations in four countries, ASN launched Abortion Without Borders to help people in Poland access abortions.
[src:dugald-baird/abortion-support-network] As of 2024, ASN has made over £1,400,000 in grants to people seeking abortions, and has been contacted by 10,000 people.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] Baird was born in Greenock on 16 November 1899 to David Baird, head of the science department at Greenock Academy, and his wife May.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] He studied science and medicine at the University of Glasgow, graduating with an MB ChB in 1922 and went on to receive an MD with honours.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] His early experiences attending births in the Glasgow slums and in the city's Royal Maternity Hospital shaped his interest in the social and economic influences on the health of women, their babies, and across generations.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] He was awarded Fellowship of the Royal College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists in 1935.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] He moved to Aberdeen in 1936 as Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] During the next three decades, his main interests were in the areas of clinical practice, service provision and health policy in reproductive health, perinatal and maternal mortality, social obstetrics, sterilisation, induced abortion, and cervical screening.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] With his wife Lady Matilda Deans Baird, also a physician, Baird established the first free family planning clinic in Aberdeen.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] In 1951 he set up the Aberdeen Maternity and Neonatal Databank, which continues today to link all the obstetric and fertility-related events occurring to women from a defined population.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] Baird and his wife had four children, two daughters and two sons.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] Their daughter, Joyce Baird worked as a doctor specialising in diabetes at the Western General Hospital in Edinburgh.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] Baird, was instrumental in gaining approval for the use of RU-486 in the UK as an emergency contraceptive.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] Euan Baird, retired as CEO and Chairman of the Board of Schlumberger Ltd. in 2003, after a long career with the company.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] In 1966, the Freedom of the City of Aberdeen was conferred on Baird and his wife for their contribution to medical science and health in the City and beyond.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] He received an honorary doctorate from the University of Stirling in 1974.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] The antenatal clinic at Foresterhill had been named after him in 1970.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] The Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health at Aberdeen Maternity Hospital is named in his honour.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] He and his wife are commemorated by plaques at 38 Albyn Place, Aberdeen.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] The Baird Family Hospital due to open in Aberdeen in 2020 is named for him, his wife, their daughter Joyce and son David, in recognition of the medical contributions they have all made in Scotland and to the profession.
[src:dugald-baird/dugald-baird] The hospital will offer maternity, gynaecology, breast screening and breast surgery services, as well as a neonatal unit, a centre for reproductive medicine, an operating theatre suite and teaching facilities.
